{"parse":{"title":"Flopped image","pageid":6215466,"revid":757949369,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303569\">@media all and (max-width:720px){.mw-parser-output .tmulti>.thumbinner{width:100%!important;max-width:none!important}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .tsingle{float:none!important;max-width:none!important;width:100%!important;text-align:center}}</style><div class=\"thumb tmulti tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:254px;max-width:254px\"><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"margin:1px;width:252px;max-width:252px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic1.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic1.jpg/250px-Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic1.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"140\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic1.jpg/375px-Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic1.jpg/500px-Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic1.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1022\" data-file-height=\"573\" /></a></div><div class=\"thumbcaption\" style=\"clear:left\">Original image of a left-hand-drive <a href=\"/wiki/Lexus_IS_250\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lexus IS 250\">Lexus IS 250</a></div></div><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"margin:1px;width:252px;max-width:252px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic.jpg/250px-Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"128\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic.jpg/375px-Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic.jpg/500px-Lexus_IS_250_Breakwater_Blue_Metallic.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1733\" data-file-height=\"884\" /></a></div><div class=\"thumbcaption\" style=\"clear:left\">Flopped and cropped image with badge restored</div></div></div></div>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Photography\" title=\"Photography\">photography</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Graphic_arts\" title=\"Graphic arts\">graphic arts</a> a <b>flopped image</b> is a technical term for a static or moving image that is generated by a mirror-reversal of an original image across a vertical axis.  This is opposed to a <i><a href=\"/wiki/Flipped_image\" title=\"Flipped image\">flipped image</a></i>, which means an image reversed across a horizontal axis.  <i>Flopping</i> can be used to improve the subjective <a href=\"/wiki/Aesthetic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Aesthetic\">aesthetic</a> appeal of the image in question.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Use_in_advertising\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Use in advertising</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Use_in_art\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Use in art</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Image_flipping\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Image flipping</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Use_in_advertising\">Use in advertising</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Flopped_image&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Use in advertising\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>There are two main uses in advertising, one practical, and one subjective.  On a practical level, images of cars are often flopped to ensure cars look appropriate for left-hand-drive or right-hand-drive markets. This allows the results of a single production shoot to be used across markets, allowing a cost saving. On a subjective level, the direction in which a person is looking or a car appears to be travelling may be regarded as important. When placing a picture on a page of text, it is usual for depictions of people to face into the text, rather than off the page; thus, when compositing a page, a picture may be flopped so it may be placed either side of a column of text.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Use_in_art\">Use in art</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Flopped_image&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Use in art\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Cultural considerations come into play&#160;&#8212; a picture of a person eating with their left hand may be flopped for publication in a Muslim publication, due to the strong taboo against eating with the left hand in Muslim society. Similarly, <a href=\"/wiki/Vincent_van_Gogh\" title=\"Vincent van Gogh\">Vincent van Gogh</a> took the trouble to etch some of his originals in mirror-reversed form so that when printed, people in the image would appear, correctly, as right-handed.\n</p><p>An example of <i>flopping</i> is the use of <a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_Southall\" title=\"Joseph Southall\">Joseph Edward Southall's</a> painting <i>Fishermen and Boat</i> as part of the art associated with <a href=\"/wiki/Kate_Bush\" title=\"Kate Bush\">Kate Bush</a>'s album <a href=\"/wiki/Aerial_(album)\" title=\"Aerial (album)\">Aerial</a>.  The picture is flopped, and the name \"AERIAL\" added to the boat.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Image_flipping\">Image flipping</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Flopped_image&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Image flipping\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:162px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Billykid.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Billykid.jpg/160px-Billykid.jpg\" width=\"160\" height=\"243\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Billykid.jpg/240px-Billykid.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Billykid.jpg/320px-Billykid.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"329\" data-file-height=\"500\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Billykid.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Billy the Kid. <i>(Flopped <a href=\"/wiki/Tintype\" title=\"Tintype\">tintype</a> photo)</i></div></div></div>\n<p>A common movie <a href=\"/wiki/Blooper\" title=\"Blooper\">blooper</a> is a flopped image, usually and erroneously called \"<a href=\"/wiki/Flipped_image\" title=\"Flipped image\">flipped images</a>\". Flopped images are common because they can be used to correct continuity errors between shots and are hard to see without extensive examination, whereas flipped images are very obvious. Examples of these can be found on several movie blooper sites.\n</p><p>One of the most famous flopped images is this picture of <a href=\"/wiki/Billy_the_Kid\" title=\"Billy the Kid\">Billy the Kid</a> carrying a <a href=\"/wiki/Winchester_Rifle\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Winchester Rifle\">Model 1873 Winchester</a> rifle and a pistol belt with the pistol on his left. This led people to believe he was left-handed, but it was later revealed to be a flopped image due to the cartridge loading gate on the rifle being on the wrong side.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Flopped_image&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">The loading gate on a Model 1873 Winchester lever action rifle is on the right side of the receiver.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Flopped_image&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Sorenson, Ray.  <cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://artsci.wustl.edu/~rsorense/PAPERS/The%20Aesthetics%20of%20Mirror.pdf\">\"The Aesthetics of Mirror Reversal <i>Philosophical Studies</i> 100/2 (2000):175-191\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=The+Aesthetics+of+Mirror+Reversal+Philosophical+Stu